  "format": "The semi-annual physical-media summit. Sean Fennessey convenes his High Council (Chris Ryan, actor Timothy Simons, and playwright Tracy Letts) to show off recent Blu-ray and 4K acquisitions, weigh boutique labels against gutted studio home-video divisions, and answer listener mail about shelving, AV setups, and grail discs. Heavy on Vinegar Syndrome, Radiance, and rape-revenge titles. Amanda Dobbins reads the questions, mostly against her will.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The State of Physical Media",
      "note": "boutique labels up, studio divisions down",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Cockfighter",
          "year": 1974,
          "note": "The Monte Hellman / Warren Oates film Sean's Tuesday movie group tried to stream. It looked like a 480p snuff film, so he ordered the disc from the UK."
        },
        {
          "title": "Return to Oz",
          "year": 1985,
          "note": "Spotted on Blu-ray at a video store; goes for around $300 on eBay. Cited as proof there's demand studios won't service."
        },
        {
          "title": "Red Sun",
          "year": 1971,
          "note": "Charles Bronson and Toshiro Mifune Western, coming from Arrow: an example of majors licensing catalog out rather than restoring it in-house."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Ascent",
          "year": 1977,
          "note": "Larisa Shepitko's Russian war film; Simons finally cracked open a disc he'd owned for four years."
        },
        {
          "title": "In the Realm of the Senses",
          "year": 1976,
          "note": "Nagisa Oshima; Letts watched it for the first time this year, with the nanny."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Parent Trap",
          "year": 1998,
          "note": "The Lindsay Lohan remake Fennessey wanted to show his daughter; the video store stocked only the 1961 Hayley Mills original."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sicario",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "Simons's comfort-watch confession: the movie he keeps rewatching instead of the unwatched pile."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "list",
      "heading": "The New Acquisitions",
      "note": "each councilor shows off recent discs",
      "picks": [
        {
          "by": "Chris Ryan",
          "title": "Deadly Outlaw: Rekka",
          "year": 2002,
          "note": "Takashi Miike, from a Radiance V-Cinema Yakuza box. Ryan's claim: the greatest opening five minutes ever filmed, scored to Flower Travellin' Band."
        },
        {
          "by": "Timothy Simons",
          "title": "Thriller: A Cruel Picture",
          "year": 1973,
          "note": "Christina Lindberg rape-revenge title from Vinegar Syndrome. Got a standing ovation from the Tuesday-night crew."
        },
        {
          "by": "Timothy Simons",
          "title": "Network",
          "year": 1976,
          "note": "On 4K. Covers the week's obsessions: Robert Duvall, 1976, physical media."
        },
        {
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "title": "The Movie Orgy",
          "year": 1968,
          "note": "Joe Dante's 276-minute mashup of film and TV ephemera, from AGFA. Long thought unreleasable; you can drop in anywhere."
        },
        {
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "title": "At Close Range",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "James Foley's rural noir with Walken and Penn, from Vinegar Syndrome's Cinematograph line. Hardcover book edition; 40th anniversary this week."
        },
        {
          "by": "Timothy Simons",
          "title": "Going Places",
          "year": 1974,
          "note": "Bertrand Blier's Depardieu breakout, from Cohen. Two irredeemable men roam France; Ebert called it 'truly cynical decadence.'"
        },
        {
          "by": "Tracy Letts",
          "title": "Cutter's Way",
          "year": 1981,
          "note": "Ivan Passer noir with Jeff Bridges and John Heard, on 4K from Radiance. The fourth boutique edition Letts has bought of it."
        },
        {
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "title": "Titicut Follies",
          "year": 1967,
          "note": "Anchors a BFI Frederick Wiseman set (also High School, Hospital, Juvenile Court, Welfare) Fennessey raced to buy after Wiseman's death."
        },
        {
          "by": "Tracy Letts",
          "title": "The Stunt Man",
          "year": 1980,
          "note": "Richard Rush's movie-about-movies with Peter O'Toole, from Radiance's Transmission label. Comes with postcards nobody can bring themselves to mail."
        },
        {
          "by": "Tracy Letts",
          "title": "Lifeguard",
          "year": 1976,
          "note": "Fun City's Sam Elliott film, brought last year and watched on a Tuesday. A beach-party premise that turns into a tone poem on aging."
        },
        {
          "by": "Tracy Letts",
          "title": "The Gambler",
          "year": 1974,
          "note": "Karel Reisz's James Caan film, from Cinematograph/Radiance. Letts's father took him to see it in a theater in 1974, at age nine."
        },
        {
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "title": "Boyz n the Hood",
          "year": 1991,
          "note": "Criterion's John Singleton Hood trilogy: Fennessey's argument for where the Collection can go once it's past the Janus canon."
        },
        {
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "title": "Poetic Justice",
          "year": 1993,
          "note": "Janet Jackson and Tupac road-trip melodrama; part of the Singleton set and, Fennessey argues, among their best performances."
        },
        {
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "title": "Baby Boy",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "Long stuck on DVD; a Tyrese and Ving Rhames melodrama Fennessey calls classical, almost Sirkian."
        },
        {
          "by": "Chris Ryan",
          "title": "Excalibur",
          "year": 1981,
          "note": "John Boorman's King Arthur swing, in a deluxe Arrow edition. A childhood obsession, and the first on-screen sex Ryan ever saw: Gabriel Byrne in a suit of armor."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mephisto",
          "year": 1981,
          "note": "Klaus Maria Brandauer as an actor selling his soul in Nazi Germany, from Second Run's Istvan Szabo trilogy. One of the best film performances on record."
        },
        {
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "title": "I Spit on Your Grave",
          "year": 1978,
          "note": "Meir Zarchi's ur-rape-revenge text, in Umbrella's 'Day of the Woman' set with a book of essays and postcards."
        },
        {
          "by": "Chris Ryan",
          "title": "Red Rooms",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Pascal Plante's French-Canadian thriller, from Utopia. Ryan's pick for one of the best and most relevant films of the decade."
        },
        {
          "by": "Tracy Letts",
          "title": "Suicide Club",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "Sion Sono, on 4K from Umbrella. Letts prefers it to Audition; opens with 54 schoolgirls jumping in front of a train."
        },
        {
          "by": "Tracy Letts",
          "title": "The Curse of Frankenstein",
          "year": 1957,
          "note": "A dictionary-sized Hammer box with six discs, a graphic novel, and posters: the episode's live unboxing bit."
        },
        {
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "title": "Death by Hanging",
          "year": 1968,
          "note": "Anchors 'Radical Japan,' a seven-film Oshima set from Radiance (also Boy, Diary of a Shinjuku Thief, The Man Who Left His Will on Film)."
        },
        {
          "by": "Timothy Simons",
          "title": "Death Game",
          "year": 1977,
          "note": "Grindhouse Releasing edition with Sondra Locke and Colleen Camp; later remade by Eli Roth as Knock Knock. Praised for Locke's theatrical ending."
        },
        {
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "title": "Ladies and Gentlemen, the Fabulous Stains",
          "year": 1982,
          "note": "Diane Lane fake-band cult movie restored to 4K by Fun City. Fennessey is annoyed he got the standard edition, sans postcards."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The Mailbag",
      "note": "grails, white whales, and 2026 releases",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Near Dark",
          "year": 1987,
          "note": "Kathryn Bigelow vampire film and long-lost-to-physical grail; an April Fools' 4K announcement left the council unsure whether it was real."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Outfit",
          "year": 1973,
          "note": "John Flynn crime thriller coming on 4K from Arrow. Simons's DVD of it was his first bona fides with Quentin Tarantino."
        },
        {
          "title": "The General",
          "year": 1926,
          "note": "Buster Keaton, coming to 4K from Eureka. One of the mailbag's most-anticipated 2026 releases."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hud",
          "year": 1963,
          "note": "A long-standing Criterion white whale, finally announced."
        },
        {
          "title": "Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore",
          "year": 1974,
          "note": "Coming from Criterion alongside Boxcar Bertha: the last two Scorsese features that were unavailable on Blu-ray or 4K."
        },
        {
          "title": "Harry and Tonto",
          "year": 1974,
          "note": "Art Carney's Oscar winner, and Fennessey's plea for a Paul Mazursky rescue: most of Mazursky's '70s run is unavailable even on Blu-ray."
        },
        {
          "title": "A Canterbury Tale",
          "year": 1944,
          "note": "Powell and Pressburger; Fennessey's grail after falling for it on TCM. He wants a good edition of a title he missed the window on."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Conformist",
          "year": 1970,
          "note": "Bertolucci; Letts can't understand why there's no 4K of the film cinematographers cite most in Visions of Light."
        },
        {
          "title": "California Split",
          "year": 1974,
          "note": "Altman gambling film in need of an upgrade; Fennessey's second-favorite Altman after Nashville."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Third Man",
          "year": 1949,
          "note": "Fennessey's go-to library recommendation: a black-and-white noir best appreciated in a high-quality edition."
        },
        {
          "title": "Miller's Crossing",
          "year": 1990,
          "note": "Ryan's library pick: a Coen film comforting enough to rewatch four times, and probably new to a casual browser."
        },
        {
          "title": "Illustrious Corpses",
          "year": 1976,
          "note": "Francesco Rosi's institutional-corruption thriller from Radiance. Ryan's Italian-crime library pick."
        },
        {
          "title": "Don't Look Now",
          "year": 1973,
          "note": "Nicolas Roeg; Letts's library pick, with 4K editions from both Criterion and Studio Canal."
        }
      ]
    }
